      Don=E2=80=99t use market orders!
   =20
 =20

There are two ways to buy stock: market orders and limit orders.
  [1]
=C2=A0A limit order says: =E2=80=9CI would like to buy 100 shares of Amalga=
mated Widgets at $20 or less.=E2=80=9D If the stock is available at $20 or =
less, you get your shares. If it=E2=80=99s not, you don=E2=80=99t. You don=
=E2=80=99t know for sure if your order will be executed, but you do know th=
e maximum price.=C2=A0A market order says: =E2=80=9CI would like to buy 100=
 shares of Amalgamated Widgets at whatever price I can get.=E2=80=9D You kn=
ow the order will be executed, but you don=E2=80=99t know at what price.
Market orders are famously risky, because occasionally prices surprise you.=
=C2=A0So 99.99% of the time, what happens is that you see Amalgamated Widge=
ts stock trading at $20 per share, and you say =E2=80=9CI would like some o=
f that,=E2=80=9D and you put in an order to buy 100 shares of Amalgamated W=
idgets at whatever the market price is, and by the time you press the butto=
n on your order and it runs through your broker=E2=80=99s systems and gets =
to the trading venue and gets filled, the price is, like, $20.01, or $20.02=
