ms that Fishback is defaming Greenlight by telling people that he was. Here=
 is the complaint; a sample:

Fishback also used false statements in his frivolous lawsuit as an improper=
 opportunity to publicly misrepresent his role and performance at Greenligh=
t by falsely claiming that he was =E2=80=9Can outstanding performer at Gree=
nlight,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cexcelled in his work,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgener=
ated over $100 million in profits for Greenlight from the period of Februar=
y 2021 to August 2023.=E2=80=9D
None of this is true. In fact, Fishback was such a poor performer at Greenl=
ight that Greenlight had actually decided to terminate him for his lack of =
productivity and scheduled a meeting with him to do so, but he abruptly res=
igned when he deduced that he was about to be terminated. And, since he had=
 absolutely no authority or discretion whatsoever over Greenlight=E2=80=99s=
 macro investment portfolio, he was not responsible for generating any prof=
its, let alone =E2=80=9Cover $100 million=E2=80=9D of profits.

Fishback is a fairly young person who was hired at Greenlight in a somewhat=
 unconventional=C2=A0way. (He =E2=80=9Cis a self-taught investment professi=
onal who successfully ran his own hedge fund for five years,=E2=80=9D said =
his lawsuit, and =E2=80=9Cpersonally consulted Greenlight=E2=80=99s founder=
 and CEO, David Einhorn, on macro investing beginning in early April 2019,=
=E2=80=9D before actually being hired at Greenlight in 2021.) He worked the=
re as an analyst covering macro, and=C2=A0he claims that he is responsible =
for the performance of Greenlight=E2=80=99s macro portfolio.=C2=A0Greenligh=
t says that in fact Einhorn was the only person with investing discretion, =
Fishback just researched ideas for Einhorn, and in fact he didn=E2=80=99t d=
o a very good job, in part because he=C2=A0was distracted by his extracurri=
cular activity of=C2=A0running a high school debate program. It is hard to =
convey, in a legal complaint, that someone was not a very good hedge fund a=
nalyst, but Greenlight tries:

Throughout 2022, Greenlight provided Fishback with clear notice that he was=
 not meeting expectations. For instance, on April 19, 2022, Mr. Einhorn exp=
ressed disappointment with the lack of substance in an assignment that Fish=
back had taken six days to complete and expressed to him that he thought Fi=
shback=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cwork, as shown, could be replicated in about 30mi=
nutes.=E2=80=9D
In Fishback=E2=80=99s formal year-end performance assessment for 2022, Gree=
nlight also communicated to him that =E2=80=9C[w]hen projects are assigned =
by David to James, they often don=E2=80=99t get evaluated in a timely manne=
r and sometimes not at all=E2=80=9D (emphasis added). The assessment contin=
ued that: =E2=80=9C[t]o summarize: we aren=E2=80=99t sure whether the lack =
of work is because (a) James disagrees with the topic, so he refuses to ind=
ulge David=E2=80=99s request in a passive/aggressive way, (b) James isn=E2=
=80=99t capable of investigating these types of questions, or (c) James isn=
=E2=80=99t committing enough hours to his work at Greenlight.=E2=80=9D

And Einhorn emailed him in May 2023:
We genuinely doubt you are working as a full time employee. We don=E2=80=99=
t have punch clocks and you work remotely. So, the burden of proof is on yo=
u. And, it looks like your side gig is cutting into Greenlight. In fact, it=
 really doesn=E2=80=99t appear to me that you are doing any meaningful amou=
nt of work for Greenlight. If I didn=E2=80=99t like you, I=E2=80=99d fire y=
ou now. But, you are on very, very thin ice.=C2=A0
And here is a tantalizing project:

Greenlight=E2=80=99s patience with Fishback finally ran out in late July 20=
23. On July 26, 2023, Fishback submitted a draft essay (the =E2=80=9CJelly =
Donut Assignment=E2=80=9D) to Mr. Einhorn that he had been assigned to writ=
e in February 2023. After many delays, the draft essay was finally supposed=
 to be delivered on July 24, 2023. Despite it being two days beyond the mos=
t recent deadline, and despite Fishback have having had months to complete =
the Jelly Donut Assignment, the draft essay appeared to reflect only a few =
hours of effort
After receiving the Jelly Donut Assignment on July 26, and determining that=
 it did not reflect a substantial amount of work, Greenlight reviewed its c=
omputer system and discovered that Fishback had almost no work files saved =
on Greenlight=E2=80=99s network drive, and had engaged in very little activ=
ity on Greenlight=E2=80=99s computer system. This effectively confirmed tha=
t Fishback had not put any serious amount of work into the Jelly Donut Assi=
gnment, as he would have needed to have been active in the network drive du=
ring the process in order to do so.
Moreover, since this review revealed that virtually none of Fishback=E2=80=
=99s work had been saved on Greenlight=E2=80=99s network drive, Fishback mu=
st either have been saving his Greenlight work files=E2=80=94which would ha=
ve included a vast amount of Confidential Information=E2=80=94on his person=
al devices, in direct violation of Greenlight=E2=80=99s policies and his Em=
ployment Agreement, or he did not do any meaningful work during his entire =
tenure at Greenlight.

Casual Googling suggests that David Einhorn really likes jelly donuts as a =
macroeconomic metaphor, so I assume that that is what was going on here, bu=
t I must say that I really want to read Fishback=E2=80=99s allegedly slapda=
sh essay about jelly donuts. It was apparently so bad that Fishback had to =
pull a you-can=E2=80=99t-fire-me-I-quit:

On Monday, July 31, 2023, Mr. Einhorn=E2=80=99s assistant emailed Fishback =
at 10:48 a.m. to inform him that Mr. Einhorn wanted to schedule a Zoom call=
 for noon that day. The unstated purpose of that Zoom call was to terminate=
 Fishback=E2=80=99s employment.
In response, at 10:56 a.m., Fishback requested that the Zoom call be resche=
duled to 3:30 p.m. allegedly due to his travel schedule. Then, a mere 27 mi=
nutes after delaying the Zoom call, Fishback tendered his resignation to Gr=
eenlight via email, and provided notice that his last day of employment wou=
ld be on August 15, 2023.

And then he went around telling everyone he was the =E2=80=9Chead of macro.=
=E2=80=9D In his lawsuit, Fishback proposed two bits of evidence for that: =
That title appeared on his bio at some conference appearances, and he had a=
 screenshot of an email from Greenlight Chief Operating Officer Daniel Roit=
man describing him that way. Greenlight=E2=80=99s lawsuit disagrees:=C2=A0H=
e=C2=A0gave himself the conference titles, and =E2=80=9CGreenlight did not =
know that Fishback had even registered as a speaker for the Citi Conference=
, let alone used the fictitious =E2=80=98Head of Macro=E2=80=99 title.=E2=
=80=9D And:

The screenshot was an email from Mr. Roitman to Ms. Heather Robinson, a Sen=
ior Manager of the GLG Group on May 11, 2023 (the =E2=80=9CGLG Email=E2=80=
=9D). The email thread began with Ms. Robinson contacting Mr. Roitman to pr=
omote a =E2=80=9CRemote Roundtable=E2=80=9D meeting her firm was hosting, a=
nd offering to =E2=80=9Csave [] a seat=E2=80=9D for Greenlight. In response=
, Mr. Roitman asked Ms.=C2=A0Robinson to sign Fishback up for the meeting, =
which was relevant to Fishback=E2=80=99s duties as a Research Analyst focus=
ed on macro positions, and introduced Fishback onto the email thread by inf=
ormally remarking that he is =E2=80=9Cour head of macro.=E2=80=9D
To be clear, Mr. Roitman was not stating that this was his formal title, as=
 is obvious from the context and lack of a proper noun. The Remote Roundtab=
le was a GLG =E2=80=9CSignature Event=E2=80=9D available only to senior exe=
cutives (only Mr. Einhorn and Mr. Roitman were invited), and Mr. Roitman ex=
aggerated his description of Fishback so that GLG would allow him to attend=
 the event.

So yeah I mean he was a=C2=A0little=C2=A0bit head of macro, in the sense th=
at everyone at a financial firm is the head of something: Sometimes you wan=
t to inflate the importance of your analyst to get him into a meeting.
Sorry, I know this is so petty, but it gets pettier:

On January 10, 2024, Fishback emailed Greenlight and threatened to attend G=
reenlight=E2=80=99s 2024 Annual Partner Dinner.
Many of Greenlight=E2=80=99s investors, counterparties, service providers a=
nd employee family members attend Greenlight=E2=80=99s Annual Partner Dinne=
rs. Fishback=E2=80=99s threats were obvious attempts to intimidate and emba=
rrass Greenlight, and interfere with Greenlight=E2=80=99s relationships wit=
h its investors, counterparties and service providers. When Greenlight noti=
fied Fishback that he was not permitted to attend, he insisted that he woul=
d still attempt to do so, or at a minimum, stand outside the event venue an=
d attempt to communicate with attendees.

He didn=E2=80=99t actually do that, but it=E2=80=99s a funny threat. Also h=
e said=C2=A0mean things about Greenlight in his Twitter bio:
On June 2, 2024, Fishback quite childishly changed the bio of his X account=
 to read: =E2=80=9CPast: Head of Macro at Greenlight (sucks)=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9CPast: Head of Macro at Greenlight (ew),=E2=80=9D as shown below.
Greenlight also says:
Overall, Fishback seems to have accomplished his goal of generating the pub=
licity he sought. Fishback=E2=80=99s posts themselves were widely viewed, w=
ith some receiving more than one million views. Major media outlets covered=
 the =E2=80=9Cdispute=E2=80=9D that Fishback pretextually procured, includi=
ng the New York Times, Business Insider, Yahoo Finance, Bloomberg and Morni=
ngstar, and as a result, his wrongful statements have been published to mil=
lions more.
Yes that is going to continue happening.

