<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two ways to buy stock: market orders=
 and limit orders.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0A limit order says: =E2=80=9CI would like to buy 100 shares of Am=
algamated Widgets at $20 or less.=E2=80=9D If the stock is available at $20=
 or less, you get your shares. If it=E2=80=99s not, you don=E2=80=99t. You =
don=E2=80=99t know for sure if your order will be executed, but you do know=
 the maximum price.=C2=A0A market order says: =E2=80=9CI would like to buy =
100 shares of Amalgamated Widgets at whatever price I can get.=E2=80=9D You=
 know the order will be executed, but you don=E2=80=99t know at what price.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Market orders are famously risky, because occa=
sionally prices surprise you.=C2=A0So 99.99% of the time, what happens is t=
hat you see Amalgamated Widgets stock trading at $20 per share, and you say=
 =E2=80=9CI would like some of that,=E2=80=9D and you put in an order to bu=
y 100 shares of Amalgamated Widgets at whatever the market price is, and by=
 the time you press the button on your order and it runs through your broke=
r=E2=80=99s systems and gets to the trading venue and gets filled, the pric=
e is, like, $20.01, or $20.02, or $19.98 or whatever, and you get your shar=
es at a slightly different price from the one that you saw on the screen, a=
nd you say =E2=80=9Cah that=E2=80=99s fine=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Coh well, sl=
ippage,=E2=80=9D and you understand that pressing the buttons on your retai=
l brokerage=E2=80=99s website is not an exact science but it=E2=80=99s good=
 enough.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then 0.01% of the time, what happens is th=
at you see Berkshire Hathaway Inc. Class A shares trading at $185 per share=
, and you say =E2=80=9CI would like some of that,=E2=80=9D and you put in a=
n order to buy 100 shares of BRK/A at whatever the market price is, and by =
the time the order gets filled, uh, 90 minutes later, the price is $741,971=
.39 per share, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/35846600.259286/aHR0cHM6Ly9maW5hbmNlLnlhaG9vLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ludGVyYWN0aXZlLW=
Jyb2tlcnMtdHJhZGluZy1ub3RpY2UtMTIzNjAwMzg2Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
a9da8f72" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">you get a bill for $74 million instead of the $18,500 you=
 expected</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the morning of Monday, June 3, 2024, at app=
roximately 9:50 am EDT, the price of Berkshire Hathaway Class A shares (=E2=
=80=9CBRK A=E2=80=9D) suddenly plummeted in the space of a few seconds from=
 approximately $622,000 per share to approximately $185 per share. This occ=
urred as part of an unspecified technical issue at the New York Stock Excha=
nge (=E2=80=9CNYSE=E2=80=9D). This technical issue and dramatic price event=
 led NYSE to promptly halt BRK A from trading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">News of BRK A=E2=80=99s anomalous price drop q=
uickly spread across social media. Some of the clients of the various broke=
rage subsidiaries of Interactive Brokers Group, Inc. (together with its sub=
sidiaries, the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D), in an apparent attempt to take a=
dvantage of this =E2=80=9Copportunity,=E2=80=9D submitted market buy orders=
 during the trading halt, presumably expecting those orders to be filled at=
 approximately $185/share when trading resumed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Without any further notice and without address=
ing a substantial order imbalance that developed during the halt, NYSE resu=
med trading of BRK A at approximately 11:35:54 am EDT at a price of $648,00=
0. Over the next 98 seconds, the price of BRK A rose to as high as $741,971=
.39 per share. Many of the Company=E2=80=99s clients that had placed market=
 buy orders during the trading halt were filled at various prices during th=
is run-up, including some who were filled at the peak price.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incredible stuff. The main point to make here =
is that, while $741,971.39 is in some sense the =E2=80=9Cwrong=E2=80=9D pri=
ce for BRK/A =E2=80=94=C2=A0Berkshire Hathaway Inc.=E2=80=99s extremely hig=
h-priced main share class =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is much, much, much closer to t=
he =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D price than $185 is. The stock has traded in the =
low $600,000s all month, other than the June 3 anomalies, and of those anom=
alies $185 was considerably more anomalous than $741,971.39. But what seems=
 to have happened is something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For glitch reasons, the price fell fr=
om $622,000 to $185.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Recognizing t=
he glitch, NYSE halted trading.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It=
 took almost two hours to restart trading.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">During that time, NYSE kept taking orders to trade BRK/A, which wo=
uld execute upon the reopening.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ma=
ny of those orders came from professional market makers, high-frequency tra=
ding firms, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Those professiona=
l orders would normally take the form of limit orders on both sides of the =
market, a sort of schedule of supply and demand.=C2=A0A market maker might =
put in orders like =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d=C2=A0buy 2=C2=A0shares at $621,000,=
 and I=E2=80=99d buy 10=C2=A0more at $620,000, and I=E2=80=99d buy 20 more =
at $619,000, or I=E2=80=99d sell 2 shares for $623,000, and I=E2=80=99d sel=
l 10 more for $624,000, and I=E2=80=99d sell 20 more for $625,000.=E2=80=9D=
 And=C2=A0the exchange would build up an order book of limit orders around =
what market makers figured was the fair price, with some orders right aroun=
d that fair price (the =E2=80=9Cmidpoint price=E2=80=9D) and others further=
 away.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also, though, during =
that time, people =E2=80=9Cacross social media=E2=80=9D saw that BRK/A had =
traded at $185, a 99.97% discount to its real value.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">They thought =E2=80=9Cah, super, a sale on BRK/A.=E2=80=
=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So they put in limit orders to=
 buy the stock at a price no higher than, say, $190 per share, a bit above =
where it last traded.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">No, I=E2=80=
=99m kidding. I mean, maybe some of them did. Maybe some investors=C2=A0put=
 in limit orders to buy BRK/A during that halt, with limit prices of $185 o=
r=C2=A0$190 or $200 or $1,000. And none of those orders were executed, beca=
use by the time the stock reopened it was trading at $648,000. Which is fin=
e. You saw BRK/A trading at $185, you thought =E2=80=9Cah, that would be a =
good deal,=C2=A0<em>if I could actually get it</em>,=E2=80=9D you put in an=
 order saying =E2=80=9Cif I can really get BRK/A at these prices, I=E2=80=
=99d like to,=E2=80=9D and you were slightly disappointed but surely not su=
rprised that you couldn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">But at least some Interactive Brokers customers instead put in=C2=A0=
<em>market=C2=A0</em>orders to buy BRK/A at whatever price it traded at whe=
n it reopened. Which was=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=A0</em>not going to be $185.=
 It was going to be $622,000.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Exce=
pt it wasn=E2=80=99t $622,000 either:=C2=A0<em>So many=C2=A0</em>people app=
arently put in market orders to buy BRK/A, because they saw it trading at a=
 discount, that =E2=80=9Ca substantial order imbalance =E2=80=A6=C2=A0devel=
oped during the halt.=E2=80=9D And so the professional market makers, seein=
g that there were more buyers than sellers in the order book, raised=C2=A0<=
em>their=C2=A0</em>limit orders, so that the new midpoint price was closer =
to $648,000. And even so, the imbalance of market buy orders ate through th=
e order book, so that all of the market makers=E2=80=99 sell orders were ex=
ecuted until the stock traded at $741,971.39, and some of those retail orde=
rs were filled at that price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And =
then, once all the retail market orders were executed, the stock went back =
to normal. BRK/A was trading around $628,000 by 12:15.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense, if you tried to buy Berkshire H=
athaway A stock=C2=A0using market orders because you read on social media=
=C2=A0that you could get it at a 99.97% discount to fair value, and instead=
 you ended up getting it at almost a 20% premium to fair value, that is you=
r fault and you deserve what you get. These people, Interactive Brokers pre=
sumes, were not steamrolled by market volatility while they were trying to =
buy Berkshire Hathaway at a normal price: They were trying to take it from =
people who were accidentally selling it at a discount, and they deserved to=
 get steamrolled.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in some other sense, that=E2=80=99s not go=
od customer service, and it=E2=80=99s also kind of risky. (What if you real=
ly did have $20,000 in your account and tried to buy 100 shares? How is you=
r broker going to get $74 million out of you?) So that Interactive Brokers =
press release that I quoted goes on:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Company determined to take ove=
r a substantial portion of these trades as a customer accommodation. The Co=
mpany also promptly filed claims for compensation with NYSE. On June 25, 20=
24, NYSE notified the Company that it had denied those claims in full. As a=
 result, the Company has realized losses (including losses on certain hedge=
 transactions) in the amount of approximately $48 million.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you did this dumb trade, Interactive Broker=
s fixed it for you: They took over the trades and ended up buying a lot of =
BRK/A stock for roughly $48 million more than it was worth.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> Interactive Brokers also =E2=80=9Cfiled a clearly erroneous execution =
(=E2=80=98CEE=E2=80=99) petition with NYSE and certain other U.S. exchanges=
, seeking to bust the trades that had occurred at anomalously high prices d=
uring the disorderly market that followed the resumption of trading.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the exchanges declined to bust the trades,=
 apparently on the reasoning that those trades were=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>=
clearly erroneous. Paying $648,000, or even $741,971.39, for BRK/A shares i=
s not crazy. Paying $185 is. The customers <em>tried</em> to buy the stock =
at clearly erroneous prices, but they ended up buying it at=C2=A0regular pr=
ices. Erroneously. <em>They</em> made the error, not the market.</p>
