<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Archegos tapes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is some elite investment bank chief execu=
tive officer performance:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jefferies calls CEO Rich Handler, =
who is on holiday in Turks and Caicos with a spicy margarita on the way. Th=
ey tell him Archegos isn=E2=80=99t answering their calls. Handler says he=
=E2=80=99s going to get his cocktail and he wants Archegos positions gone a=
nd a tally of losses by the time he comes back. It was one of the few banks=
 that escaped with minimal losses.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Perfect. When your underlings call you up and =
say =E2=80=9Chey we have a big trading counterparty that lost a lot of mone=
y, we=E2=80=99re sending margin calls and they=E2=80=99re not answering the=
 phone,=E2=80=9D the correct answer is =E2=80=9Cliquidate them immediately,=
=E2=80=9D but the=C2=A0<em>stylish </em>(and equally correct) answer is =E2=
=80=9Cliquidate them by the time my margarita arrives.=E2=80=9D Handler han=
dled Archegos way better from his=C2=A0vacation than <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35846600.259286/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN=
5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyNjI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNjI2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB79941383" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Credit Suisse ha=
ndled it at the office</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That anecdote is from Ava Benny-Morrison and S=
ridhar Natarajan=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/35846600.259286/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlc=
y8yMDI0LWJpbGwtaHdhbmctYXJjaGVnb3MtY29sbGFwc2UtdGltZWxpbmUvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2=
MjYyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDYyNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB1e7e6f36" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">hair-raising minute-by-minute account of the final days=
</a>=C2=A0of Archegos Capital Management, Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s family offic=
e, which blew up in 2021. Hwang is now on trial for market manipulation and=
 fraud, and the trial features a lot of his bankers testifying about how th=
ey were tricked into lending him tons of money to finance his big stock bet=
s, and more particularly how they let him=C2=A0<em>keep=C2=A0</em>the money=
 for a few extra hours or days in March 2021 while Archegos was imploding.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The essential problem was this. Archegos had a=
 portfolio of giant leveraged bets on about a dozen stocks. In some cases, =
it was the biggest single owner of those stocks, but since it owned the sto=
cks through total return swaps at a bunch of different banks, that was not =
apparent: As far as anyone could tell from public data, each bank had a rea=
sonably sized position in each of those stocks (to hedge its swaps to Arche=
gos); there was no single large owner. But then some of the stocks went dow=
n, Archegos got margin calls on its big leveraged swap bets, it couldn=E2=
=80=99t meet the margin calls, and all the banks had to seize and sell the =
stocks at the same time. This drove down the prices of the stocks, evaporat=
ed=C2=A0Archegos (which went from a net worth of $36 billion to zero) and l=
eft some banks with big losses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not Jefferies, though, or not so much. The tri=
ck is that if you=C2=A0<em>immediately=C2=A0</em>seized Archegos=E2=80=99s =
stocks and sold them, you got out at a decent price and didn=E2=80=99t lose=
 money. If you waited too long, the prices melted down and you lost money. =
Handler, at the swim-up bar,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0grasped the essential issue and blew out Archegos=E2=80=99s posit=
ions at Jefferies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Others did not, because they didn=E2=80=99t re=
alize how bad things were for Archegos, because =E2=80=94=C2=A0the governme=
nt alleges =E2=80=94=C2=A0Archegos misled them about its actual positions. =
In the government=E2=80=99s telling, each bank=C2=A0<em>thought=C2=A0</em>t=
hat Archegos had a portfolio of (1) big leveraged bets on a dozen stocks at=
=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>bank plus (2) boring, straightforward investments =
in household-name stocks at all the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So=C2=A0at 3 p.m. on Wednesday, March 24, 2021=
, a UBS Group AG risk manager sent colleagues an email about Archegos=E2=80=
=99s 20+% losses on some of its swaps with UBS, which would lead to a large=
 margin call the next day. =E2=80=9CNo immediate concern,=E2=80=9D the risk=
 manager wrote, =E2=80=9Cgiven the excellent performance in the past year a=
nd they are giving back the gain.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Archegos=E2=80=99s deal with UBS seems to have=
 been that it needed to post margin each day based on the previous day=E2=
=80=99s prices. So that Wednesday, Archegos was flush with cash, because al=
l of its trades were profitable=C2=A0<em>as of Tuesday</em>. In fact, it wa=
s so flush with cash that it had an extra $173 million in its UBS account: =
Based on Tuesday=E2=80=99s prices, it could demand $173 million of margin=
=C2=A0<em>back=C2=A0</em>on Wednesday. Of course by Wednesday afternoon, UB=
S and Archegos both knew that on=C2=A0<em>Thursday</em>, Archegos would hav=
e to post a lot more margin, to reflect its losses on Wednesday.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Archegos asked for the money anyway: It as=
ked UBS to send it $173 million on Wednesday afternoon, understanding that =
it would have to send back $500 million or so on Thursday. Somewhat crazily=
, in hindsight, UBS was like =E2=80=9Csure fine here you go.=E2=80=9D There=
=E2=80=99s a snippet of taped conversation between UBS risk manager Bryan F=
airbanks and Scott Becker, Archegos=E2=80=99s head of risk, at 3:15 p.m. We=
dnesday:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fairbanks: This is Bryan.<br />Bec=
ker: Hey Bryan, it=E2=80=99s Scott=C2=A0from Archegos, how are you?<br />Fa=
irbanks: Hey Scott, how are you doing?<br />Becker: Doing well. Sorry I too=
k a while to get back to you, I apologize.<br />Fairbanks: No problem, no p=
roblem. I just wanted to give you guys a heads up, obviously there=E2=80=99=
ll be a sizeable call tomorrow.<br />Becker: Yeah, that makes sense, thank =
you.<br />Fairbanks: Um I was to be honest a little surprised you guys put =
in the wire today for the excess since you=E2=80=99ve been leaving with us =
for a while.<br />Becker: Yeah, would that =E2=80=94 would that be okay?=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would not be okay, it turns out! But Fairba=
nks approved the wire; there=E2=80=99s an email from him at 7:23 p.m. to hi=
s colleagues, saying:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I spoke with client; he knows that=
 there is a sizable call tomorrow and confirmed that their losses are mostl=
y at UBS as their bigger positions are relatively flat (Amazon, Google, etc=
.). I approved the wire so expecting ~$500m call tomorrow. Client agreed to=
 acknowledge and pay promptly and we=E2=80=99ll of course watch very closel=
y tomorrow and send a note out once we collect.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The story here was that Archegos had big losse=
s=C2=A0<em>at UBS</em>, which would require it to post $500 million of marg=
in on Thursday, but it would have no problem doing that, because its positi=
ons at=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>banks were =E2=80=9Crelatively flat (Amazon=
, Google, etc.).=E2=80=9D In fact, its positions at other banks were the sa=
me as its positions at UBS, it was going to get margin calls from all of th=
em, and it was withdrawing $173 million from UBS on Wednesday to have a cha=
nce at meeting some other margin calls on Thursday. Bad!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By=C2=A0<em>9:57 that night</em>, Archegos=E2=
=80=99s co-chief executive officer, Andy Mills, told UBS:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Frankly, you know, we don=E2=80=99=
t see how we=E2=80=99re gonna be able to meet those margin calls fully by t=
omorrow evening at 6 o=E2=80=99clock, and so I wanted to get ahead of that =
and just describe what we are doing so that you know where we=E2=80=99re co=
ming from on this, and to give you our assurance that we will get through t=
his very quickly. The first thing I want to say is this is a liquidity issu=
e, not a solvency issue.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That turned out to be wrong, but that=E2=80=99=
s not the point. The point is that that call is=C2=A0<em>two and a half hou=
rs=C2=A0</em>after the UBS risk manager emailed his colleagues to say he wi=
red Archegos $173 million, despite knowing he=E2=80=99d be asking for $500 =
million the next day, because the client assured him they would meet the ma=
rgin call. And now they said they would not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It got considerably worse the next day. At 6:4=
3 a.m. on Thursday, Archegos trader William Tomita did a call with Fairbank=
s and Ashley McLucas at UBS:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">McLucas: How common are those name=
s across your other providers, you know in terms of, what we see, is that v=
ery similar to what you=E2=80=99ll be seeing across all your providers, or =
is it quite different?<br />Tomita: I think those concentrated names, are a=
 common one at multiple brokers, a lot of the liquid US and tail names are =
much more varied.<br />Fairbanks: So meaning you have =E2=80=94 you said Vi=
acom, Discovery, Tencent =E2=80=94 you have those names away as well in siz=
e?<br />Tomita: In meaningful size, yep.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, less than 12 hours earlier, Fairbanks w=
as emailing that Archegos had =E2=80=9Cconfirmed that their losses are most=
ly at UBS as their bigger positions are relatively flat (Amazon, Google, et=
c.).=E2=80=9D Turns out, nope, same positions everywhere, same losses every=
where.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMy gut sunk,=E2=80=9D said Fairbanks in court.=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9CI knew UBS was going to take a very large loss.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Others didn=E2=80=99t know that yet. At 11:44 =
a.m., Archegos Chief Financial Officer Patrick Halligan sent an Instant Blo=
omberg message saying =E2=80=9CMufg [Mitsubishi UFG Financial Group Inc.] l=
iterally told will good luck, no big deal. Best counterparty award.=E2=80=
=9D You don=E2=80=99t want to win Archegos=E2=80=99s best counterparty awar=
d! (MUFG lost $270 million.) You want to be the worst counterparty.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The worst counterparty was Goldman Sachs Group=
 Inc.: As we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35846=
600.259286/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQt=
MDUtMjgvYXJjaGVnb3Mtc2VudC1nb2xkbWFuLXNvbWUtZnJlZS1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjI=
2MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG=
1fdGVybT0yNDA2MjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
bbe164c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">discussed a while back</a>, Archegos had a $470 million c=
ollateral surplus at Goldman on Wednesday and tried to call it back. (As it=
 did with its $173 million at UBS.)=C2=A0But instead, Archegos accidentally=
 <em>sent</em> Goldman an extra $470 million, leaving it with $940 million =
of extra collateral on Wednesday. (Though presumably with much less on Thur=
sday, given how the positions moved on Wednesday.) Archegos asked Goldman f=
or the money back and Goldman said =E2=80=9Clol no.=E2=80=9D That is the co=
rrect answer! UBS was off sending Archegos every penny it asked for, which =
was a mistake. Goldman saw where things were going and kept the money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thursday was a lot of Archegos telling the ban=
ks =E2=80=9Cjust sit tight, the check is in the mail,=E2=80=9D until at 8:2=
2 p.m. =E2=80=9CHwang finally speaks up in a hastily arranged call with a l=
arge group of anxious banks.=E2=80=9D They did not like what they heard, an=
d at 6:47 a.m. on Friday, March 26, 2021, =E2=80=9Cthe default notices from=
 banks start pouring in,=E2=80=9D and the banks start liquidating Archegos=
=E2=80=99s stocks. Some move slowly =E2=80=94=C2=A0Credit Suisse tries to s=
ell carefully not to spook markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0while others move quickly=
: Goldman shops a block trade of its ViacomCBS position, and Handler, at 1:=
30 p.m. on Friday, gives the =E2=80=9Csell it all before I get my drink=E2=
=80=9D order.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I once talked to a hedge fund executive about =
his prime brokerage relationships. Hedge funds often rely on borrowing mone=
y from their brokers, and it is important for the hedge funds to be confide=
nt that, in a crisis, the brokers will be there for them. If your positions=
 move against you and you get a margin call from your prime brokers, you wa=
nt to be able to say =E2=80=9Cgive us one more day and we=E2=80=99re good f=
or it,=E2=80=9D and you want them to say =E2=80=9Cfor you, sure, one more d=
ay.=E2=80=9D How, I asked, do you manage that? What is it that gets you goo=
d treatment from prime brokers in your time of need? Is it writing ironclad=
 contracts that give you locked-up financing? Is it being a good customer w=
ho pays them a lot of money in the good times, so they=E2=80=99ll keep you =
afloat in the bad times? Is it being nice to them personally, so they like =
you?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He said that what matters is that they think y=
ou=E2=80=99ll make it. If they think you=E2=80=99re going bankrupt, they ar=
e going to want to get their money out. Their personal fondness for you, yo=
ur past business, all the fees you=E2=80=99ve paid them, even the specific =
terms of the contract: All of that is yesterday=E2=80=99s news; what matter=
s is if you=E2=80=99ll be around to pay them back tomorrow. The only trick =
is to build a reputation for being careful, for being a survivor, for runni=
ng only risks that won=E2=80=99t blow you up. If your prime brokers think t=
hat you=E2=80=99re a survivor, they=E2=80=99ll help you survive. If they do=
n=E2=80=99t think you=E2=80=99re a survivor, you won=E2=80=99t be.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess this is obvious? But Archegos is, alle=
gedly, the fraud version of it. If all your prime brokers think that you ar=
e a family office with stable long-term funding and a portfolio consisting =
mostly of boring positions in household-name stocks, they will each let you=
 make a few spicy bets with <em>them</em>. And when those bets move against=
 you and you get big margin calls, they won=E2=80=99t move too quickly to c=
lose you out: You have all those safe positions everywhere else, you have p=
lenty of money, you=E2=80=99re good for it. And then if it turns out that y=
our entire portfolio is spicy bets everywhere and you go to zero in three d=
ays, the banks will understandably feel defrauded.</p>
